  <h3>Promoted for the work, handed the people</h3>
  <p>Most managers were promoted for being good at the work. They hit their numbers, ran their projects well, knew the job inside and out. So they got the title, and with the title came a job that's mostly people: motivating them, developing them, hearing them, holding them accountable, sitting across from them in the hard conversations.</p>
  <p>Almost nobody gets trained for that part. The training that exists covers the project side: processes, reviews, planning, deadlines. The people side gets learned by trial and error, on real employees, and the errors are expensive. They show up as turnover, as quiet teams, as problems that surface late because nobody wanted to raise them.</p>
  <p>Here's the reframe underneath everything we teach. A manager isn't just a title. It's a role in another person's life. And the human side of that role is not a personality trait some people have and some don't. It's a skill, and skills can be taught.</p>

  <h3>Manage With Meaning</h3>
  <p>The workshop covers the human side of leadership in two connected halves.</p>
  <p>The first half is the human connective: <em>how to mean it.</em> What actually builds trust with a team, what motivates people beyond the paycheck, how to give feedback that changes things instead of bruising things, and how to be authentic while still holding boundaries. This is the half that determines whether a team brings their manager the truth.</p>
  <p>The second half is the company objective: <em>how to meet it.</em> Delegation that develops people instead of just distributing tasks. Accountability that focuses on impact, not just effort. Decision making, putting the right person in the right job, and connecting each person's work to why it matters. This is the half that turns a trusted manager into an effective one.</p>
  <p>Running through both is one steady theme: a manager has an impact on every person who reports to them, whether they're paying attention to it or not. The impact is happening either way. This workshop puts it in their hands.</p>

  <h3>What's included</h3>
  <p>Managers leave with tools built for real moments, not binders built for shelves: a communication handbook, a vocabulary guide, and pocket phrases with a leadership quick reference for the situations that actually come up, accountability conversations, delegation, conflict, and coaching.</p>
  <p>They also receive team-understanding worksheets for applying the work to the specific people they manage, and ongoing access to the materials as their teams change and grow.</p>
  <p>For managers who want to go further, individual coaching is available, built around their real team and the real situations they're navigating.</p>
